abindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Sept 23, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104dej1665702891569.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/dej1665702891569.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/dej1665702891569.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"dej1665702891569\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Defining COM Components\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body taskbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">To define COM components, make the appropriate definitions in the Signature Editor.\n </p>\n<section><ol class=\"ol steps\"><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"dej1665702891569__li_d18062e1_d18063e1_d18064e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Within the Signature Editor, define a component with COM as its Implementation. See <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"zzx1665702678830.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/zzx1665702678830.html\" title=\"Use the Signature Editor to create or modify component signatures. Signatures of Uniface components are automatically generated during compilation. Signatures of non-Uniface components can be created or imported.\">Define a Component Signature</a>.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"dej1665702891569__li_d18065e1_d18066e1_d18067e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Specify the information about the component’s operations and their parameters.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"dej1665702891569__li_d18068e1_d18069e1_d18070e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">In the Define COM Properties form, specify the <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"tzb1665702753850.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/tzb1665702753850.html\" title=\"Name of the COM ProgID.\">ProgID</a> or <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"xjr1665702753919.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/xjr1665702753919.html\" title=\"Internal class ID of the COM component. It is automatically provided when the ProgID is selected.\">CLSID</a> of the COM object that implements the service.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"dej1665702891569__li_d18071e1_d18072e1_d18073e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"dej1665702891569__p_d35294e1_d35295e1_d35296e1\">In the Define Parameter form, specify the\n               parameter attributes for each operation. </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<p class=\"p\">Pay particular attention to the <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"woi1665702807515.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/woi1665702807515.html\" title=\"Uniface data type of the parameter. The data type and implementation determine the other properties that can be set for this parameter.\">Data Type</a> setting. The\n                  availability of other fields, such as <span class=\"ph uicontrol\">Interface</span> or\n                     <span class=\"ph uicontrol\">Literal Name</span>, depends on the data type for the\n                  particular parameter.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"dej1665702891569__p_d35297e1_d35298e1_d35299e1\">The value of the <span class=\"ph uicontrol\">Literal\n                     Name</span> field is stored in the COM Interface DD when it is created,\n                  and is available to COM applications that use these services. A Uniface occurrence\n                  is mapped to COM’s ADOR. Recordset type with a single or number of\n                  occurrences.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"dej1665702891569__p_d35300e1_d35301e1_d35302e1\">If you want to map a COM data type to a Uniface\n                  data type, you should select the appropriate Interface from the drop-down\n                  list:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dej1665702891569__li_d18074e1_d18075e1_d18076e1\">If you want to pass a number of occurrences\n                     of an entity to a COM service, you should define the parameter as having data\n                     type Entity. </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dej1665702891569__li_d18077e1_d18078e1_d18079e1\">If you need to pass a single occurrence of\n                     an entity as a parameter to a COM service, select the Occurrence data type for\n                     the parameter. </li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</li></ol></section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/oxz1665702649123.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>COM and Uniface Parameter Data Types</a><p>Converting Uniface parameter data types to and from the COM environment has both a static and dynamic nature. When you export a COM Interface DLL, the data types of the signature definitions must be matched to the appropriate COM types, taking into account the user’s implementation selections. At runtime, both Uniface and COM allow the user to pass variants for parameters, so the connector can dynamically convert data types, within reason.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2526764\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2526764\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Defining COM Components Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Sept 23, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Defining COM Components To define COM components, make the appropriate definitions in the Signature Editor. Within the Signature Editor, define a component with COM as its Implementation. See Define a Component Signature . Specify the information about the component’s operations and their parameters. In the Define COM Properties form, specify the ProgID or CLSID of the COM object that implements the service. In the Define Parameter form, specify the parameter attributes for each operation. Pay particular attention to the Data Type setting. The availability of other fields, such as Interface or Literal Name , depends on the data type for the particular parameter. The value of the Literal Name field is stored in the COM Interface DD when it is created, and is available to COM applications that use these services. A Uniface occurrence is mapped to COM’s ADOR. Recordset type with a single or number of occurrences. If you want to map a COM data type to a Uniface data type, you should select the appropriate Interface from the drop-down list: If you want to pass a number of occurrences of an entity to a COM service, you should define the parameter as having data type Entity. If you need to pass a single occurrence of an entity as a parameter to a COM service, select the Occurrence data type for the parameter. Related Links COM and Uniface Parameter Data Types Converting Uniface parameter data types to and from the COM environment has both a static and dynamic nature. When you export a COM Interface DLL, the data types of the signature definitions must be matched to the appropriate COM types, taking into account the user’s implementation selections. At runtime, both Uniface and COM allow the user to pass variants for parameters, so the connector can dynamically convert data types, within reason. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}